{"actual_usd":0.157825,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":305,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"No—Christians don’t mean three separate beings who happen to share a title.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees a little, the morning light laying a pale stripe across my white tie while the square wakes up around us.* \"We mean one God in three persons: the Father is God, the Son is God, the Spirit is God—and yet the Father is not the Son, the Son is not the Spirit, and the Spirit is not the Father.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of my Bible a moment.* \"If that sounds like it won’t fit neatly in a little box, that’s because it won’t. ‘Hear, O Israel: The Lord our God, the Lord is one’ stays true. And then the New Testament forces your hand—Jesus speaks to the Father, is sent by the Father, sends the Spirit, and yet receives the honor due to God. So the church didn’t invent a puzzle for fun; it was trying not to lie about what Scripture had handed it.\"\n\n\"It’s monotheism because the being of God is one, not divided into three gods.\" *I glance up toward the clear sky for half a beat.* \"The mystery is not one God wearing three masks, and not three gods in a committee. It’s one divine being, eternally Father, Son, and Spirit.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short ‘heresies-to-avoid’ version too—that’s usually the clearest next step.\"","rolling_24h_usd":31.235990000000015,"run_id":"fbc2d7c3-e228-40e6-875e-95dc82545b56"}
